  "prompt": "Does every dog has rabies?",
  "response": "No, not every dog has rabies. Rabies is a viral disease that affects the central nervous system and is transmitted through the saliva of infected animals, typically through a bite. While all mammals, including dogs, can potentially contract rabies, not all dogs are infected.\n\nRabies is relatively rare in dogs in many countries, especially in places where there are effective vaccination programs for pets and wildlife. In fact, widespread vaccination of dogs has been one of the most effective strategies in reducing rabies cases in both animals and humans.\n\nHowever, in areas where vaccination rates are low and rabies is more prevalent in wildlife, the risk of dogs contracting and transmitting rabies is higher. Signs of rabies in dogs can include behavioral changes, aggression, excessive drooling, difficulty swallowing, paralysis, and ultimately death.\n\nTo protect dogs and reduce the risk of rabies:\n\n1. **Vaccinate dogs regularly**: Rabies vaccination is often required by law in many countries and regions.\n2. **Avoid contact with wild animals**: Keep dogs away from potentially rabid wildlife, such as bats, raccoons, skunks, and foxes.\n3. **Report stray or sick animals**: If you see a dog or other animal acting strangely, contact local animal control or public health authorities.\n\nBy taking these precautions, the risk of a dog contracting rabies can be significantly reduced.",
